},
{
	"fnNumber": "21",
	"fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.27:2.1–2.2</span> &amp; <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;1.10:14.1–14.2</span>. The Chinese parallels of <span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.27</span> (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sa601' class='extlink'>SĀ 601</a> and <a href='https://suttacentral.net/sa-2.176' class='extlink'>SĀ-2 176</a>) appear not to have “where earth, water, fire, and air find no footing”. Cf. <span class='sesame biblioref'>Sujato 2011b</span>.</p>"
},
{
	"fnNumber": "22",
	"fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;8.1:3.1–3.4</span></p>"
},
{
	"fnNumber": "23",
	"fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>SN&#8239;1.27:2.5–2.6</span> mentions the cessation of <span lang='pi'>nāmarūpa</span>. In <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;1.10:12.3–15.4</span> the verses were spoken when monks asked about the faith of the arahant Bāhiya who just passed away. <span class='sclinktext'>Ud&#8239;8.1</span> mentions the absence of all form and the formless. All other factors in this inspired utterance describe the end of rebirth from different perspectives. So all three texts are about nibbāna after death.</p>"
},
{
	"fnNumber": "24",
	"fnHTML": "<p><span class='sclinktext'>MN&#8239;98:11.55–11.58</span> <span class='ptsref'>PTS: M II 121</span> &amp; <span class='sclinktext'>Dhp&#8239;409</span></p>"
},
